It seems there is some confusion in the provided examples, especially with the repeated and incorrect responses for converting ENSG00000149476 to an official gene symbol. Let's clarify this process step-by-step:

### Step 1: PUT BLAST Request

To perform a BLAST search using the NCBI BLAST service, you would typically use a `PUT` request to submit your sequence and receive an RID (Request ID). Here is how you can do it for the given DNA sequence:

```plaintext
https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/blast/Blast.cgi?CMD=Put&PROGRAM=blastn&MEGABLAST=on&DATABASE=nt&FORMAT_TYPE=XML&QUERY=ATTCTGCCTTTAGTAATTTGATGACAGAGACTTCTTGGGAACCACAGCCAGGGAGCCACCCTTTACTCCACCAACAGGTGGCTTATATCCAATCTGAGAAAGAAAGAAAAAAAAAAAAGTATTTCTCT&HITLIST_SIZE=5
```

This request will return an RID, which you can use to retrieve the results later.

### Step 2: GET BLAST Results

Once you have the RID from the PUT request, you can use it in a `GET` request to fetch the BLAST results:

```plaintext
https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/blast/Blast.cgi?CMD=Get&FORMAT_TYPE=Text&RID=<your_RID>
```

Replace `<your_RID>` with the actual RID returned from the PUT request.

### Example for Converting ENSG00000149476 to Official Gene Symbol

To convert an Ensembl gene ID (like ENSG00000149476) to an official gene symbol, you can use the Entrez Utilities:

#### Step 1: Search for the Gene ID

First, perform a search using the `esearch` utility:

```plaintext
https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esearch.fcgi?db=gene&retmax=10&retmode=json&sort=relevance&term=ENSG00000149476
```

This will return a list of gene IDs that match the Ensembl ID.

#### Step 2: Fetch Gene Summary

Use the `efetch` utility to get more details about the gene, including its official symbol:

```plaintext
https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esummary.fcgi?db=gene&retmax=10&retmode=json&id=<gene_id>
```

Replace `<gene_id>` with the ID returned from the `esearch` request.

### Step 1: PUT BLAST Request

To perform a BLAST search using the NCBI BLAST service, you would typically use a `PUT` request to submit your sequence and receive an RID (Request ID). Here is how you can do it for the given DNA sequence:

```plaintext
https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/blast/Blast.cgi?CMD=Put&PROGRAM=blastn&MEGABLAST=on&DATABASE=nt&FORMAT_TYPE=XML&QUERY=ATTCTGCCTTTAGTAATTTGATGACAGAGACTTCTTGGGAACCACAGCCAGGGAGCCACCCTTTACTCCACCAACAGGTGGCTTATATCCAATCTGAGAAAGAAAGAAAAAAAAAAAAGTATTTCTCT&HITLIST_SIZE=5
```

This request will return an RID, which you can use to retrieve the results later.

### Step 2: GET BLAST Results

Once you have the RID from the PUT request, you can use it in a `GET` request to fetch the BLAST results:

```plaintext
https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/blast/Blast.cgi?CMD=Get&FORMAT_TYPE=Text&RID=<your_RID>
```

Replace `<your_RID>` with the actual RID returned from the PUT request.

### Example for Converting ENSG00000149476 to Official Gene Symbol

To convert an Ensembl gene ID (like ENSG00000149476) to an official gene symbol, you can use the Entrez Utilities:

#### Step 1: Search for the Gene ID

First, perform a search using the `esearch` utility:

```plaintext
https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esearch.fcgi?db=gene&retmax=10&retmode=json&sort=relevance&term=ENSG00000149476
```

This will return a list of gene IDs that match the Ensembl ID.

#### Step 2: Fetch Gene Summary

Use the `efetch` utility to get more details about the gene, including its official symbol:

```plaintext
https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esummary.fcgi?db=gene&retmax=10&retmode=json&id=<gene_id>
```

Replace `<gene_id>` with the ID returned from the `esearch` request.
